post_cb({"21263661": {"ParentId": "21263381", "CommentCount": "4", "Body": "<p>Later the standard says \"Every object of static storage duration is zero-initialized at program startup before any other initialization takes place.\" So if you have e.g. in global scope</p>\n<pre><code>int x;\nint&amp; r = x;\n</code></pre>\n<p>r is first zero-initialized, and then initialized by x. For reference, zero-initialized means nothing, so it is mere technicality.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "2382136", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "21263661", "Score": "16", "CreationDate": "2014-01-21T16:24:33.483", "LastActivityDate": "2014-01-21T16:24:33.483"}, "21263381": {"CommentCount": "10", "AcceptedAnswerId": "21263661", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "1708801", "CreationDate": "2014-01-21T16:12:15.470", "LastActivityDate": "2014-01-21T16:59:44.307", "LastEditDate": "2014-01-21T16:59:44.307", "ViewCount": "350", "FavoriteCount": "3", "Title": "When would a reference be zero-initialized?", "Id": "21263381", "Score": "17", "Body": "<p>\u00a78.5/6 in draft <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2013/n3797.pdf\">N3797</a> says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_21263381_21263381_0\">To zero-initialize an object or reference of type T means:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>...</li>\n<li>if T is a reference type, no initialization is performed.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'd like to have an example of a reference that is zero-initialized.</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><initialization><language-lawyer>", "OwnerUserId": "2337207", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_21263381_21263381_0": {"section_id": 3285, "quality": 1.0, "length": 5}}, "n3337": {"so_21263381_21263381_0": {"section_id": 3155, "quality": 1.0, "length": 5}}, "n4659": {"so_21263381_21263381_0": {"section_id": 653, "quality": 0.8, "length": 4}}}});